This year, let's make a big leap toward the full promise of #JuneTeenth and freedom. Let's change Ally-ship from being a noun to being a verb.

Being an ally is not about feeling something, it is about doing something. To get started, pick one element from this list, or begin with any other intention you have in mind - hopefully this thread has given you ample ideas and idea-starters.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

Don’t let bad behavior go without commenting on it. Allies can work to establish better meeting protocols and training, and they can also speak up when those protocols aren’t followed.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

Help all team members recognize the word choices, inhibitors and negative speech patterns that undermine participation and, ultimately, keep the company from achieving its full potential by keeping individuals from achieving their full potential.

Tone management is really tough, but not insurmountable. Negative language and tone are a subtle but powerful way to silence others, and meetings are one place that masters of subtlety ply this skill. Encourage your company to include “tone training” in your meeting training.

This contributes to treating all the ideas more equitably, and reduces the impact of some people being repeatedly silenced while other people always see their ideas advanced.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

After the brainstorming is done, ideas can be rated, prioritized, and eliminated. The benefit is that by the time you get to the rating portion of the meeting, the ideas have been separated from the people who proposed them.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

Another way to marginalize people is to criticize their ideas. A method that leads to better results for the company & raises confidence and contributions of marginalized people is to use brainstorming liberally, with a "no idea can be criticized during brainstorming" rule.

Allies can also undo an interruption by saying, “hold on a minute, I want to hear what she was trying to say.”
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

A “no-interruptions” rule in company discussions, trained and ingrained through corporate culture and training, is the best way to eliminate this behavior.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

This was said earlier, but it’s so important that it bears repeating. One of the fastest, easiest ways to marginalize someone is to talk over them.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

This is also an effective way to make sure marginalized voices are invited and heard. Allies can do the work of asking these questions. Or go one step further and work to get your company to train every meeting leader to ask them.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

Companies that train meeting leaders to ask 1) has everyone who has an opinion on this agenda item had a chance to speak? and 2) is there anyone who has a contrary opinion on this agenda item that hasn’t been heard yet? make better decisions.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

Allies can also speak up when someone who should be in a meeting is not invited. Get them in the room.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

Meetings should include the right people to bring the background to, brainstorm solutions to, and solve problems. Using an SME strategy can help ensure that the right people are included.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

One of the ways people of color are disadvantaged in companies is by being left out of meetings, and the excuse for this is almost always “it’s bad to have too many people in a meeting.” There is no right size for meetings. There is only a right composition.

Changing the way meetings are structured and conducted could make a material difference to any person struggling to find equal footing in a business environment.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

A surprising amount of the work of corporations – and therefore the perceived value of individual members – takes place in meetings. Meetings are also where copious examples of bad human behavior come from.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

Use ROTAs and objective performance data to ensure that all SMEs can contribute as project leaders and receive assignments that will help them grow personally and professionally. A rotation strategy helps create equal opportunity for all to take on projects, learn, and shine.

Managers are often unaware of the attributes of all their team members. An SME strategy makes capabilities, certifications, and skills objective and visual, and takes the subjectivity out of project and task assignments.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

Grant project and task opportunities based on ability. Use an SME (Subject Matter Expert) method to identify project leaders and the pool of talent for each assignment type. This will help correct for managers that assign tasks based on personal comfort with certain team members.

Eliminate the requirement of a college degree for jobs that do not actually require a college education. Look for opportunities to make jobs available to someone who has no prior experience, but shows potential for development. 
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

The requirement to disclose “felony conviction” on job application forms disproportionately affects people of color, because it is well-documented that activities that result in a misdemeanor charge for a white person will often result in a felony charge for a person of color.

Allies can also accomplish a great deal by improving or petitioning to improve the job application process.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

Managers should also be required to track performance evaluation data several times throughout the year, to reduce the likelihood that end-of-year performance evaluations will be based on vague assessments.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

If the employee did not specifically tell the manager she was not interested in promotion due to those reasons, the manager should not be able to include his assumption as an evaluation point.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

If a manager writes, “She isn’t interested in a promotion at this time because she has two small children and an elderly parent to care for,” that is an assumption that should be challenged.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

Companies need to make performance evaluations more objective by using rating systems and requiring managers to demonstrate the rationale for their ratings. It is also important to eliminate assumptions in the evaluation process. For example,

Most companies only track employee demographics to assess diversity goals, but applicant pools should be tracked as well. Call for your company to self-assess on how final hiring decisions look relative to general population and the applicant pool each hire came from.

If your company can offer a relief fund for employees to tap into and pay back on extended, no-interest terms, many families could be saved (jobs too!).
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

People of color are far less likely to have access to money from savings, loans, or friends-and-family in a crisis. This means that a crisis of $400 can them in a situation of desperation or homelessness.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

People of color often struggle with integrating into new work environments, because part of job success is establishing a welcoming and supportive peer group. Propose onboarding programs that help new employees effectively integrate into the company and succeed.

So are training initiatives that teach people to be better listeners, how to search out and benefit from diverse opinions, how to manage meetings, and how to structure projects, assign work, and manage teams.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

Ask for anti-racism training throughout your company, then go further. Training programs that promote cultural awareness and sensitivity, DEI (diversity, equity, inclusion) initiatives, and individual bias assessments and training are also important.

Promote an intentional culture in your company (or work group) by establishing a set of agreed-upon principles to guide how people work with one another.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

Advocate for full health care for all employees, not just employees at certain levels. Even better, put your company’s influence behind support for national health care. People of color and single mothers suffer disproportionately from lack of access to affordable health care.

Besides, companies that provide better leave policies have lower turnover and higher employee commitment than companies that do not.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

Advocate for paid parental and sick leave. Women of color are far less likely to be able to afford leave after having a child than white women. Maternal care has lifelong implications for individual, family, and community health, so this is an important ally intention to tackle.

Compensation isn't just about how much people are paid, it's also about what they can do while being paid. Advocate for all employees to be able to participate in democracy. Ask your organization to make election day a paid holiday or to offer sufficient paid time off to vote.

Companies that do a good job of data-driven motivation, performance analysis, and compensation tend to outperform companies that do not.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

Work to make sure pay is awarded to employees based on objective data like specific responsibilities and measured performance. This requires a management approach that uses data to monitor progress in all areas – which sounds like a lot of work, but it is a win/win.

Do not leave living wage to the political arena, to be tainted by politics. Advocate within your own company.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

If your company doesn't pay a living wage to all, advocate for living wage policies inside your company. This is both good ally work and good for the company. Statistics show companies that pay well are more profitable, and living wage communities have better economies.

If you are not an owner or senior executive of your company, it will be tempting to discount your ability to influence change. Do not give in to this impulse. The work of an ally is also about bringing attention to issues, advocating for change, and forming coalitions.

Achieving balance in a group should not be a passive activity – it should be active, outward looking, and intentional. If you don’t have sufficient diversity in your group, go find it.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

Look for balance. Any group you work in should reflect the gender and cultural diversity of the community it serves and/or belongs to. Set intentions around recruiting and including people to ensure your group is representative of your population.

Even if the behavior is just based on bad manners (white guy interrupts white guy), call it out. Gently redirect with, “Hey, we have a commitment to not interrupt each other here. I’d like to hear what he was trying to say.”
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

Speak out. This is the most difficult for most people. When you see a person treat another with disrespect, hear a joke, jab, or comment that comes from (and reinforces) bias, or observe one person interrupting another, these are all opportunities to address bias at its source.

Implement ROTAs (rotations) for housekeeping tasks. Everyone gets a scheduled turn taking minutes, organizing refreshments, cleaning the coffee area, cleaning the bathrooms . . . you get the drift. ROTAs help eliminate caste assignments that reinforce bias & stereotyping.

Team principles like no interrupting, everyone gets the opportunity to express their ideas and opinions, no criticisms during brainstorming, and a requirement to demonstrate equal respect for everyone in the group in words, tone, and action can be surprisingly impactful.

Every type of organization should have a no-tolerance-for-racism policy that is supported by training. If your organization does not have one, start here. Suggest it. Advocate for it. Enlist others. Don't stop until you have one.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

One does not have to be the boss or the leader of a group to influence change. Here are some ideas for goals you can set to mitigate bias while working in any context.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

In each of the non-personal spheres (business, community, spiritual, political) there is an aspect of work: People assembling to do administrative tasks, pursue initiatives, and work on projects. Allies can achieve a lot by changing the way groups work together.

The only way to become a more conscious person is to take time to reflect. Adopt the discipline of a daily recap, during which time you reflect on your interactions throughout the day, and question if and how your actions were influenced by unconscious bias.

So accept that you will get it wrong, and that graciously accepting feedback and getting past the embarrassment is part of the important work of ally-ship.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

Take the feedback. If you are lucky, you have friends who are people of color - friends who will tell you when you’re getting it wrong. There is no instruction handbook for being an ally, and walking in someone else’s shoes is great in theory, but nearly impossible in practice.

When we learn to listen without defense, we hear more, learn more.
#JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

Listen without defense. It's hard to accept responsibility for things that happened before we were born or that are perpetuated by systems that we didn't set up. It is infinitely more difficult to be disadvantaged by those things. #JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter
By setting a goal to slow down and question our decisions, we make the space necessary to see if those decisions are being driven by bias. #JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

move to a different bench in the park, tell our child "no" to an outing with friends, or avoid house shopping in a specific neighborhood, we are often making the decision from an unconscious place. #JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

Slow down & question reactions and decisions.  Our unconscious is in the drivers’ seat most of the time. So the only way to take back the wheel is to slow down. When we decide to cross to the other side of the street, avoid walking into a particular store,

Human beings are wired to inherently trust people whom we perceive to be more like us, and distrust those whom we perceive are less like us. As a result, we are all guilty at some level of sustaining the current system with unconscious bias. #JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter

Engage in situations that involve people from diverse backgrounds. The work of being an ally cannot be merely theoretical. While being an ally to entire groups of people is important, being an ally to specific people will bring greater understanding and empathy to your ally-ship.

Learn about the history of racism and racial injustice and how the system perpetuates inequality. Take classes or workshops, read books, attend lectures, listen to podcasts. Abundant resources exist to help allies learn more and be more effective. #JuneTeenth2021

In our personal lives we have control over what we know and learn; what we say, think, and do; and how we respond to what others say and do — so all these areas are ripe for actionable goals. #JuneTeenth2021 #blacklivesmatter
